SassDoc is a documentation system for Sass that turns your source code and
inline comments into a full‑featured reference website. It brings the kind of
developer experience people expect from tools like JSDoc to the Sass ecosystem.

{% info %}
**Disclaimer:** SassDoc is no longer actively maintained. It remains totally
usable though, and will still work as expected even in modern Sass codebases.
{% endinfo %}

## How it works

- **Inline annotations**: you document your mixins, functions, variables and
  placeholders using structured comments directly in your `.scss` files.
- **Static generation**: a CLI parses those comments and emits a static site
  that can be hosted anywhere alongside your project or design system.
- **Search and navigation**: the generated UI makes it easy to browse APIs,
  filter by type, and jump straight to what you need.

Because the documentation lives next to the code, it is much easier to keep
it in sync as things evolve.

## Why it matters

SassDoc was designed to support teams working on shared Sass toolkits, design
systems and large codebases where “just reading the source” is no longer
practical. It encourages better habits around documenting intent, not just
implementation details, and helps newcomers build a mental model of what is
available.

The project is open‑source and has been used by many teams to document both
internal and public Sass libraries, including the [Guardian](https://www.kaelig.fr/gu/guss-sassdoc/),
the [Financial Times](https://github.com/search?q=repo%3AFinancial-Times%2Forigami%20sassdoc&type=code)
and [Norton](https://wwnorton.github.io/design-system/sassdoc/).

